04623nam a22005655i 9780231538183DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014004973  a(OCoLC)984656951  a97802315381837 a10.7312/pand169902doi  a(DE-B1597)458459  a(OCoLC)890707013  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ759.5b.P36 2014 4aHQ759.5b.P36 2014 7aFAM0320002bisacsh04a1762221 aPande, Amrita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWombs in Labor :bTransnational Commercial Surrogacy in India /cAmrita Pande.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia Across the Disciplines00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Wombs In Labor -- t2. Pro-Natal Technologies in an Anti-Natal State -- t3. When the Fish Talk about the Water -- t4. Manufacturing the Perfect Mother-Worker -- t5. Everyday Divinities and God’S Labor -- t6. Embodied Labor and Neo-Eugenics -- t7. Disposable Workers and Dirty Labor -- t8. Disposable Mothers and Kin Labor -- t9. Conclusion -- tEpilogue: Did the “Sperm on a Rickshaw” Save the Third World? -- tAppendix A. Selected Clauses from the Assisted Reproductive Technologies (Regulation) Draft Bill, 2010 -- tAppendix B. Consent Form to Be Signed by Surrogates -- tAppendix C. Descriptive Tables -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSurrogacy is India's new form of outsourcing, as couples from all over the world hire Indian women to bear their children for a fraction of the cost of surrogacy elsewhere with little to no government oversight or regulation. In the first detailed ethnography of India's surrogacy industry, Amrita Pande visits clinics and hostels and speaks with surrogates and their families, clients, doctors, brokers, and hostel matrons in order to shed light on this burgeoning business and the experiences of the laborers within it. From recruitment to training to delivery, Pande's research focuses on how reproduction meets production in surrogacy and how this reflects characteristics of India's larger labor system. Pande's interviews prove surrogates are more than victims of disciplinary power, and she examines the strategies they deploy to retain control over their bodies and reproductive futures. While some women are coerced into the business by their families, others negotiate with clients and their clinics to gain access to technologies and networks otherwise closed to them. As surrogates, the women Pande meets get to know and make the most of advanced medical discoveries. They traverse borders and straddle relationships that test the boundaries of race, class, religion, and nationality. Those who focus on the inherent inequalities of India's surrogacy industry believe the practice should be either banned or strictly regulated. Pande instead advocates for a better understanding of this complex labor market, envisioning an international model of fair-trade surrogacy founded on openness and transparency in all business, medical, and emotional exchanges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSurrogate motherhoodzIndia. 0aSurrogate motherszIndia. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Parenting / Motherhood.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/pand1699040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538183423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231538183.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press